Yes, you're right! Go 1.21 introduced the built-in `clear` function which is more efficient for clearing maps (and slices). Let's update the map pool implementation:

```go
// NewMapPool creates a pool for maps with automatic clearing
func NewMapPool[K comparable, V any](initialCapacity int, name string) MapPool[K, V] {
    return &mapPool[K, V]{
        pool: New(Config[map[K]V]{
            Factory: func() map[K]V {
                return make(map[K]V, initialCapacity)
            },
            Resetter: func(m map[K]V) error {
                // Use built-in clear function (Go 1.21+)
                clear(m)
                return nil
            },
            Name: name,
        }),
    }
}
```

The `clear` built-in function is:
- More efficient than iterating and deleting
- Clearer intent
- Works on maps and slices
- No memory allocation overhead

Similarly, for slices, instead of `s = s[:0]`, we can use `clear(s)` when we want to clear the contents while maintaining capacity:

```go
// For slice pools
func (sp *slicePool[T]) Put(s []T) {
    if s == nil {
        return
    }
    clear(s)     // Clear contents
    s = s[:0]    // Reset length (if needed)
    sp.pool.Put(s)
}
```

Note: `clear(s)` sets all elements to their zero value, while `s = s[:0]` just resets the length. Choose based on your needs - if you need to zero out sensitive data, use `clear`. If you just need to reset length and don't care about the contents (they'll be overwritten anyway), `s[:0]` is sufficient.
